Puzzles solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebellum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists from the Humboldt Federal University in Berlin found out this with the help of experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday evening. Progress was also made on the question why children fight so violently against tickling, only in order to demand more.
After all, it has also been shown why only the approaching of a tickling hand causes laughter even before the touch. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebellum, which already triggers laughter in the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, earlier research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound area when they are tickled by humans. This "laughter" is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of the haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-contact
Until now it had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-contact and contact with others - hence people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found out in the experiments on rats that laughter as well as the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during a self-contact. This was also so if living beings themselves clean up. However, during the foreign contact and tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse had been intensified.
If, however, the self-touch and the touch by others at the same time, the laughter is also suppressed. This suggests that the rat ’ s brain cannot distinguish between self-contact and touch by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because the self-contact activates a brake in the brain.
The rats had also been trained to tickle themselves. Therefore, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showing escape behaviour or horror rigidity. This ambivalence is similar to the behaviour of the children. The ambivalence of the tickle is a behavioural reaction that is the same in rats and people.
