Study on Causes of Heart Diseases
Smoking, overweight, unhealthy nutrition - there are risk factors for the cardiovascular system. But what really triggers a heart weakness or an infarction? Hamburg researchers now want to look closely at the genetic material of 9000 healthy and sick people.
About the analysis of the genetic material of 9000 people Hamburg and Swiss scientists want to find out the causes of cardiovascular diseases in more detail.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking region, announced the University Hospital Hamburg (UKE) on Friday. The Kühne District Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros. The high-mountain clinic Davos, which belongs to the foundation, and the University Hospital Zurich, are involved in Switzerland.
Obesity, smoking and unhealthy nutrition are among the main influencing risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. Genetic factors determine the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is insufficiently known, it was said. Now the scientists want to compare the complete genetic material of 8000 healthy people with that of 1000 former patients of the University Heart and Vascular Centre at UKE.
More than 4000 of the 20,000 or so relevant human genes are currently known to cause possible changes in the DNA - so-called mutations -, according to the hospital. Each year about 200 additional genes are added.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of heart rhythm disorders, heart weakness and heart attacks. Data could also be used for research into other common diseases, according to Stefan Blankenberg, Head of the University Heart and Vascular Centre. New findings on the interaction between heart and brain, heart and kidney as well as on cancer are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne sondern Foundation, Klaus Moreover Michael Kühne (82), also stressed that there was a firm will to use the data also for the investigation of other diseases. Up to now, the clinic of the foundation in Davos deals mainly with allergies. Now a center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine should be created at the medical incampus there and a professorship for bioinformatics be created. To justify his engagement, the logistics entrepreneur living in Switzerland said that he had been operated at the open heart in Hamburg three years ago and was very grateful.
The bioprobes of the healthy participants originate from Hamburgers, who also participate in the "Hamburg City Health Study". With 45,000 subjects, this is the largest local health study in the world according to the hospital. In the case of genome decryption, strict attention is paid to the protection of anonymised data, the scientists assured. It is about a petabyte (1000 terabytes) of data, said Holger Moch from the University Hospital Zurich.
According to UKE, the genetic material of a human being can now be decoded within 24 hours, with a mere cost of 1300 Euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, whose results were published in 2001, still cost several hundred million Euros. The study is expected to begin on 1 October, and all 9000 samples are expected to be analysed by the end of 2020.
