Attention: Smartphone NEVER charge wirelessly
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi is extremely practical, but should not be used.
As several new smartphones have recently come onto the market that support wireless charging and sell themselves very well - above all the new iPhone 11th models, we would like to remind you of another study from the beginning of July. Although wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, it is not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature sets battery
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick, this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If a mobile phone is normally charged by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. In the case of wireless charging, the researchers have always measured more than 30 degrees even with the perfect alignment of the smartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is slightly located next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. Furthermore, the watt strength of the charging pad increases, which in turn drives up the power consumption.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature for the durability of batteries is a decisive factor. Every single degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only reduces its capacity, but also keeps it through for not so long. Therefore, the researchers advise that the smartphone should always be charged by cable. As a battery exchange with modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently even increased the cost of battery exchange - for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are meanwhile already installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels as well as cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable salad and laborious plug fummelei. Since with Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) a world-wide standard prevails, in which exceptionally even Apple participates, there are hardly restrictions. Nevertheless, the technology should be applied according to the researchers only in exceptional cases.
