Half of the European tree species are threatened with extinction
In addition to pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are causes of the threat, the World Union for the Protection of Nature IUCN reported on Friday in Brussels. It investigated the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of them do not occur on any other continent. Of these 265 58 percent are threatened. 66 are already at the highest level of danger and thus before extinction.
The IUCN divides endangered species into six categories: from "potentially endangered" via "endangered", "strongly endangered", "threatened by extinction" and "extinct in nature" to "extinct". Overall, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide than endangered.
Rowan and wild horse chestnut threatened
In Germany above all Ebereschen (Sorbus) are threatened, said one of the authors, David Allen, the German press agency. "Most are threatened, because the populations are anyway small or by the transformation or weakening of their habitats".
It also looks bad for the wild common horse chestnuts. Since 2017 they are regarded as "endangered", stage two of the IUCN -scale. Largest threat is the Balkans -Miniermotte beside a fungus. It spreads from south-eastern Europe over the whole continent since the 1980s and has hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnuts (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe on less than 10,000 specimens. In this assessment the trees in cities, parks and avenues are not taken into account.
Shrub species and mosses also in danger
More than a fifth of the molluscs and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened, according to the IUCN. This is mainly due to the destruction of the wilderness, to introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Molluscs such as snails played a key role in the recycling of nutrients in the soil and were an important source of food for birds and other animals.
"This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of the European ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet," said Luc Bas, IUCN Director of the European Office. "We must limit human impact on our ecosystems and make the protection of these species a priority".
