Green politician has to be responsible for embarrassing photo pot
The leader of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the election campaign - was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The Canadian Green Leader holds in his hand a multiplier cup in a photo. But now came out: The cup was manipulated.
Ottawa / Canada - It has remained unnoticed for quite a long time - and finally noticed nevertheless. Elizabeth May, the head of the Canadian Greens, never held the reusable coffee mug with metal straw in her hand. On the party's website she was shown in a photo with this mug, in conversation with citizens. However, the photo had already been published and also distributed to the media - and there the mug was still a frightening (Papp) mug, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Green leader must be responsible for photography
As a result, the National Post accused May of manipulation and that the party produced fake news in order to appear more credible on the subject of "environmental protection", right in the middle of an election campaign for the House of Commons, in which it has become increasingly difficult because of a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral in the social media and raised the discussion about fake news. A user shares a comparison of the photos and writes: "The Greens manipulate a photo of their chairmen to hide their disposable cup".
May was shocked and asserted on her blog that she knew nothing about this action. In order to underline this, she immediately posted the original: She, in conversation with citizens, had a cup in her hand. However, he, she correctly, was made of bamboo. She always had it with him. A spokesperson of the party said that it was only a matter of putting the party logo in the picture and not of covering up something. Of the photo, only one detail can be seen on the website.
May writes that she is suffering for the employee who has done that. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide," she says to the Guardian and asked for something from her over-committed team: "If they want to work on a picture again, then they could not do something with my face, so that I look younger?"
The German Greens have also fallen into Shitstorms because of their use of one-way plastic or because of air travel - but their pictures were not photoshopped. Thus, the boss of the Bavarian Greens, Katharina Schulze, ate ice cream on vacation with plastic spoons, as merkur.de * reported.
Influencerin wants free upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Jaqueline Ng was said to have been promised an upgrade by mail from Cathay Pacific. However, when she asked for it during the check in, she was not allowed on board - and she should never be allowed to fly again with Cathay.
Spontaneously getting an upgrade for Business Class - many passengers dream of it. Sometimes they are lucky, and the staff at the check in offer a change from Economy Class free of charge.
This case shows, however, how it should not be done: A self-declared influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. Jaqueline Ng more than 65,000 users follow Instagram. On May 30 she flew back from Taiwan to New York and on June 7.
On the outbound flight, Jaqueline staff refused to upgrade, although she had presented an email in which her Cathay Pacific allegedly offered an upgrade, which the influencerin wants to receive from a marketing assistant of the airline. Jaqueline, on the other hand, accused the airline of having forged the mail.
On the return flight Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time the woman is supposed to have shown the same mail, but with another reference number. The employees at JFK airport were skeptical: they looked after the headquarters. And actually the employee, from whom the mail allegedly originated, denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. That also confirmed the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
The airline staff at the airport canceled Jaquelines ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. For 1,400 US dollars (about 1,280 euros) they had to buy a new flight ticket to Taiwan.
With her case, the influencerin turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Cathay had reimbursed her for her original ticket, but Jaqueline also demanded the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: for Cathay, the influencerin has committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. Furthermore, the terms and conditions of the airline state that they do not have to pay the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with this - and now switches on a lawyer.
Oil prices report on ceasefire in Yemen
The oil prices fell by more than one dollar on Friday afternoon in the shortest possible time. Finally, a barrel (159 liters) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the previous day. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
A report by the Wall Street Journal on a ceasefire in Yemen triggered the price slide. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
In mid-September, a drone attack on the oil plants in Saudi Arabia had killed five percent of the world ’ s oil production. Iran ’ s allied Huthi rebels in Yemen ’ s civil war had claimed the attacks. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, is responsible for Iran. A ceasefire would defuse political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, it could focus on growth and demand, said Ole Hansen, head of the Raw Materials Strategy Division at Bloomberg ’ s Saxo Bank.
Oil prices thus continue its downward movement of the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost nearly $59, Brent nearly $65.
Bloomberg recently reported, citing insiders, that repairing oil plants in Saudi Arabia after the attack in mid-September was faster than thought. Accordingly, the production volume has returned to a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press releases citing insiders reporting rapid progress on the repair work of Saudi Aramco, a state-owned oil company. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relaxation in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leave the port more than two months after Iran's arrest and the recent release. Now, the crew prepares the departure while the ship is still anchored, shipping chief Erik Hånell informed the Swedish radio on Friday morning in an SMS.
However, the US announced that it would transfer defense missiles and soldiers to Iran ’ s arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and Great Britain had temporarily driven up oil prices considerably in recent weeks.
