Doping: Further Russian manipulations proved
Material from the Moscow analytical laboratory is manipulated – this is confirmed by David Howman, former Director of the World Antidoping Agency (Wada) and today ’ s Head of Integrity of the Athletics Federation.
At the start of the World Championships in Athletics, new details about the doping scandal are revealed in Russia - and they destroy the little credibility that the Russian sport had recovered at the beginning of the year and only partially. In January 2019, the Moscow doping laboratory finally delivered the required samples from the years 2012 to 2015 to the World Antidoping Agency (Wada).
In December 2014, systematic fraud had been revealed in Russian sport. Thereupon, the Wada had closed the Russian Anti-doping Agency (Rusada) for three years. During this period, Russian athletes were not completely banned from the world stage. After individual examination at the 2016 Summer Games in Rio, the International Olympic Committee had around 270 athletes of the country compete under neutral flag, at the Winter Games in February 2018, 168 Russian athletes were at the start. They were also allowed to participate in the World Cup in the various sports, in the summer even the Football World Cup with the host as participant took place in Russia.
Positive findings missing
In the following September, the Wada resumed the Rusada ’ s ban, but called for access to the laboratory and the samples in question. Data should provide information on the extent to which doping is covered up. They should help to punish athletes retrospectively. Three months later, they were finally delivered.
The Chairman of the Independent Integrity Commission (AIU) of the World Athletics Federation (IAAF) has now confirmed that doping has been manipulated from the Moscow Analysis Laboratory. "Yes. We received the data nine months ago. We should check whether the Task Force has received the right data," said David Howman in an interview with the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung" on Friday. "We have found numerous discrepancies between the data that the Wada received from a whistleblower and those received from the Russians in January." Many positive findings were missing, which have been mentioned in the McLaren report.
The World Cup not affected
This confirms the IAAF ’ s position: the Athletics Federation is the only organization to hold on to Russia ’ s spell. 30 Russian athletes are flying neutral at the Doha World Cup. They had to prove that they are training outside the Russian system and undergoing tests.
At the beginning of this week, Wada had already put manipulations in the room and asked Russia to respond within three weeks to the accusations. Russia is now threatening to re-block the Rusada and, in the worst case, to exclude the 2020 Olympic Games in Tokyo.
